{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CbLWtVmWF61E7hNafuWso7","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/4-4-source-isolation-enforcement.md`.\n\n**Summary:** Created story 4-4-source-isolation-enforcement with 9 acceptance criteria and 6 task groups. All ACs tagged `test-provable` -- the module does file system operations (create temp dir, copy files, cleanup) that are fully verifiable via unit tests without a running app. The story is additive only (no existing files modified) and creates `src/lib/source-isolation.ts` with a co-located test.\n\nKey design decisions carried forward from AD2 (architecture doc): temp directory approach (no git worktree, no Docker-in-Docker), cwd-based isolation via Agent SDK, and `disallowedTools: [Edit, Write]` already set on the evaluator template.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **No problems encountered.** Epic definition was clear, all referenced code exists.\n- **Workarounds applied:** None.\n- **Risks identified:**\n  - AC #4 depends on `templates/agents/evaluator.yaml` having `disallowedTools: [Edit, Write]` from story 3-2. If that template was not created or lacks this field, the AC will fail. I confirmed via grep that the existing codebase references `disallowedTools` in the evaluator context, but did not verify the YAML file directly (it may not exist yet if story 3-2 templates were not committed).\n  - The `/tmp/` path pattern is Unix-specific. On Windows, `os.tmpdir()` would differ. Not a current concern (darwin platform) but worth noting for portability.\n- **Observations:**\n  - This is the last story in Epic 4, and it is purely additive -- no existing files need modification. The module is a clean primitive that Epic 6 (evaluator) will consume.\n  - All 9 ACs are `test-provable` because the module is pure file system operations testable with real temp dirs.\n\n## Token Report\